## General procedure
- Install Ubuntu
- Install packages to compile a kernel
     - `apt-get install build-essential bc curl ca-certificates gnupg2
libssl-dev lsb-release libelf-dev bison flex dwarves zstd libncurses-dev`
     - for later Kernels (>6.3?): `apt-get install build-essential bc
curl ca-certificates gnupg2 libssl-dev lsb-release libelf-dev bison flex
dwarves zstd libncurses-dev debhelper`
- Download Kernel Sources and RT patch
     - Look for the patch with the highest available Kernel version
[here](https://mirrors.edge.kernel.org/pub/linux/kernel/projects/rt/)
     - Download the corresponding kernel
[here](https://mirrors.edge.kernel.org/pub/linux/kernel/)
- extract, patch and compile kernel
     - `gunzip patch-5.19-rt10.patch.gz`
     - `tar -xzf linux-5.19.10.tar.gz`
     - `cd linux-5.19.10`
     - `patch -p1 < ../patch-5.19-rt10.patch`
     - `cp -v /boot/config-$(uname -r) .config`
     - `make olddefconfig`
     - `make menuconfig`
         - General Setup > Preemption Model and select Fully Preemptible
Kernel (Real-Time).
         - Cryptographic API > Certificates for signature checking (at
the very bottom of the list) > Provide system-wide ring of trusted keys
 > Additional X.509 keys for default system keyring
         - Remove the “debian/canonical-certs.pem” from the prompt and
press Ok
         - "Provide system-wide ring of blacklisted keys" deselektieren
     - `date > compile_time ; make -j2 deb-pkg 2>&1 | tee compile.log ;
date >> compile_time;`
     - for later Kernels (>6.3?): `date > compile_time ; make -j2
bindeb-pkg 2>&1 | tee compile.log ; date >> compile_time;`
     - `dpkg -i ../linux-headers-5.19.10-rt10_5.19.10-rt10-1_amd64.deb
../linux-image-5.19.10-rt10*.deb`
- possibly it is not possible to select the new kernel during the boot
processe, edit grub:
     - vi /etc/default/grub
     - `GRUB_DEFAULT=SAVED`
     - `GRUB_TIMEOUT_STYLE=`
     - `GRUB_TIMEOUT=2`
- configure RT
     - `sudo addgroup realtime`
     - `sudo usermod -a -G realtime $(whoami)`
     - edit /etc/security/limits.conf
         - `@realtime soft rtprio 99`
         - `@realtime soft priority 99`
         - `@realtime soft memlock 102400`
         - `@realtime hard rtprio 99`
         - `@realtime hard priority 99`
         - `@realtime hard memlock 102400`
- now it's possible to boot the RT Kernel, but not with Secure Boot,
this issue is still open
